ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[The health facility in the Muchanga health area where health workers have become infected, as well as several cases, should be thoroughly decontaminated, and all remaining healthcare workers should be vaccinated to prevent further infection. See the MoH report below from 27 Mar 2019. It appears the community would not allow for this to take place. The facility should not be used without decontamination because new cases will occur. The community must be convinced of the infectiousness of Ebola and the need for precautionary measures to prevent further spread. But vaccination of frontline workers also must be provided for their safety. According to Helen Branswell, "so far in this outbreak 78 health workers have been infected and 27 have died". - Mod.LK]

- 27 Mar 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=fd73608885

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 26 Mar 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 1029, of which 964 are confirmed and 65 are probable. In total, there have been 642 deaths (577 confirmed and 65 probable) and 324 people recovered.
- 239 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 7 new confirmed cases, including 4 in Katwa, 2 in Beni, and 1 in Oicha.
- 3 new deaths of confirmed cases, including 2 community deaths in Katwa and 1 death at the ETC of Butembo.

News of the response
Katwa: Importance of decontamination of households and health centers
----------------------------------------------------------
- Of the 4 new confirmed cases in Katwa reported today, 3 are from the Muchanga health area. These 3 people were cared for in the same health facility in which 7 confirmed patients were hospitalized since 10 Mar 2019, indicating a possible nosocomial transmission of the virus. However, no decontamination activity could be carried out after the notification of each new confirmed case because of the refusal of the surrounding community.
- As explained in the 26 Mar 2019 newsletter, Infection Prevention and Control (ICP) is an essential pillar to break the chain of transmission of the virus and stop the spread of the virus. Thus, when a person infected with Ebola is treated in a health center, outside the ETC, decontamination of the center is important to prevent other patients from being infected later.

Vaccination
----------
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 92 172 people have been vaccinated [see URL above for total number of vaccines in each location].

