- 26 Mar 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=f5498ed440

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 25 Mar 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 1022, of which 957 are confirmed and 65 are probable. In total, there have been 639 deaths (574 confirmed and 65 probable) and 324 people recovered.
- 161 suspected cases are under investigation.
(Information unavailable for health zones covered by Butembo's sub-coordination due to an internet connection problem.)
- 6 new confirmed cases: 2 in Katwa, 2 in Mandima, and 2 in Vuhovi.
- 5 new deaths of confirmed cases, including 4 community deaths -- 2 in Katwa and 2 in Mandima -- and 1 death at the ETC in Butembo.
- 3 new patients recovered and discharged from the Butembo ETC.

News of the response
New strategy for prevention and control of community infections
----------------------------------------------------
- Following the attacks on the ETCs in Katwa and Butembo, the coordination launched community dialogues in several health zones to invite the community to share their concerns and suggestions regarding the conduct of the response to the Ebola outbreak. Many recommendations were made, and 2 pillars of the response were then targeted by coordination, namely, Infection Prevention and Control (ICP) and Risk Communication and Community Engagement (CREC).
- IPC teams are responsible for putting in place measures and practices to stop the transmission of infectious diseases in health facilities and in the community. These measures include the disinfection of health facilities and households, the installation of handwashing points, and the provision of personal protective equipment (PPE).
- Coordination organized a 1st workshop on IPC 21-23 Mar 2019 in Goma to improve the quality of ICP interventions and the perception of ICP by communities. The main recommendations of the workshop are:

1. Adapting standard ICP community-based operating procedures targeted at community engagement and integrating families into the process;
2. Developing a specific communication strategy on new approaches to community-based ICP to improve community understanding; and
3. The revitalization of the Villages and Clean Schools program and the Water, Sanitation and Hygiene projects, particularly in Butembo and Katwa.

- A 2nd workshop on risk communication and community engagement was held in Goma 25-26 Mar 2019, and recommendations will be shared shortly.

Vaccination
----------
- Since the beginning of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 91 891 people have been vaccinated [see URL above for number of vaccines at each location].

--
